**3. The SQL Editor --- How to Upload Data**

The SQL Editor is where all uploads happen. Every time you want to add
data to Supabase, you paste SQL code here.

**3.1 How to Open a New Query (CRITICAL --- Always Do This First)**

> **1.** Click \'SQL Editor\' in the left sidebar (looks like a \> \_
> icon).
>
> **2.** Click the big blue \'+ New Query\' button in the top left.
>
> **3.** A blank tab opens. Paste your SQL here.
>
> **4.** Click the green \'Run\' button (or press Ctrl+Enter /
> Cmd+Enter).
>
> **5.** You should see \'Success. No rows returned\' or a result table
> below.
>
> *WARNING: NEVER paste DROP or DELETE statements into an existing
> schema tab. Always use a fresh \'+ New Query\' tab. Pasting into the
> wrong tab has caused previous schema errors.*

**3.2 What SQL to Use --- The Two Types of Upload**

**Type 1 --- INSERT (adding new rows)**

Use this when you have new data that does not exist yet in the table.
Example:

> INSERT INTO cfi_feedstock_values (stream, parameter, value, unit,
> source)
>
> VALUES (\'EFB\', \'moisture_pct\', 62.5, \'% wb\', \'CFI canonical Mar
> 2026\')
>
> ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;

**Type 2 --- UPDATE (changing an existing row)**

Use this only for CLASS B, C, or D values (never CLASS A guardrails).
Example:

> UPDATE cfi_pricing
>
> SET price_usd = 360, effective_date = NOW()
>
> WHERE product = \'urea\' AND is_active = true;

**Type 3 --- CREATE TABLE (adding a new table)**

When Claude\'s gap analysis finds data that does not fit any existing
table, Claude will write you a CREATE TABLE statement. Paste it in a new
query tab exactly as written.

> *Always log changes in cfi_change_log after any UPDATE. Claude will
> include this INSERT automatically in every SQL block it writes for
> you.*

**4. The CFI Data Flow: File → Claude → Supabase → Dashboard**

Here is the exact journey every piece of data takes:

> • Step 1 --- You have a file: lab result PDF, Excel workbook, research
> doc, or data table.
>
> • Step 2 --- You upload it to this Claude Project chat with the CFI
> Upload Prompt (see Document 2).
>
> • Step 3 --- Claude reads the file, identifies which Supabase table
> the data belongs to, checks for duplicates, and checks for conflicts.
>
> • Step 4 --- Claude writes SQL INSERT / UPDATE / CREATE TABLE
> statements.
>
> • Step 5 --- You copy the SQL. Open Supabase → SQL Editor → New Query
> → paste → Run.
>
> • Step 6 --- Claude confirms the data is live and updates any related
> dashboard calculations.
>
> *You never write SQL yourself. Claude writes it. You paste and run.
> That is the entire workflow.*

**5. How to Check If Your Upload Worked**

After running SQL in Supabase, there are two ways to verify:

**5.1 In the Table Editor**

> **1.** Click \'Table Editor\' in the left sidebar.
>
> **2.** Find the table you just updated (e.g. cfi_feedstock_values).
>
> **3.** You should see your new row at the bottom.

**5.2 Run a SELECT Query**

In a new SQL Editor tab, paste:

> SELECT \* FROM cfi_feedstock_values ORDER BY created_at DESC LIMIT 10;

This shows the 10 most recently added rows. Your new data should be at
the top.

**5.3 Check the Change Log**

> SELECT \* FROM cfi_change_log ORDER BY timestamp DESC LIMIT 5;

Every accepted data change must appear here. If it does not, the log
INSERT was missed --- ask Claude to write a corrective log entry.

**6. CLASS A Guardrails --- What You Can NEVER Change in Supabase**

Some values are permanently locked (CLASS A). These appear in
cfi_guardrails with is_guardrail_locked = true. The UI shows them for
reference only. You cannot update them via SQL either --- they require a
code change + brief update + workbook update in the same session.

  ------------------- ---------------------- ----------------------------
  **Locked Value**    **Current Setting**    **Why Locked**

  OPDC yield          15.2% of EFB fresh     Mass balance anchor ---
                      weight                 changing breaks entire
                                             pipeline

  OPDC press MC floor 40% minimum            Below this pore damage kills
                                             BSF colonisation

  5-day biological    5 days hard rule       Biological science minimum
  minimum                                    --- cannot be shortened

  BSF intro pH gate   ≤8.0                   Above this kills BSF
                                             colonisation

  BSF intro temp gate ≤30°C                  Above this kills BSF
                                             colonisation

  N conversion factor 4.67 (not 6.25)        CFI frass-specific --- 6.25
                                             overstates protein

  PKSA cost           \$0 / t                Mill waste --- always free
                                             to CFI

  Carbon model        213,827 t CO2e/yr      Locked methodology ---
                                             ACM0022/VM0042

  Feedipedia POME EE  REJECTED permanently   Material mismatch + mass
                                             balance failure
  ------------------- ---------------------- ----------------------------

